{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01FzvmQLasF6sAJHTLNF6Nwd","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Alright, I can see the setup. The secret `es-secure-settings` is already mounted as a volume at `/run/secrets/es-secure` on each pod. The secret contains:\n- `s3.client.default.access_key`: minioadmin\n- `s3.client.default.secret_key`: minioadmin\n\nNow the key issue is: Elasticsearch uses a keystore to store secure settings, not directly mounted files. The credentials from the Kubernetes secret need to be imported into the Elasticsearch keystore.\n\nThere are two approaches:\n1. Use `elasticsearch-keystore` tool to import the keys from the mounted secret files\n2. Use the Elasticsearch API to reload secure settings after adding them to the keystore\n\nSince the keystore is persisted in the data directory and needs to survive pod restarts, the proper solution is to use an init container that populates the keystore from the mounted secret before Elasticsearch starts.\n\nHowever, since the secret is already mounted at `/run/secrets/es-secure`, I can take a simpler approach: exec into each pod and use `elasticsearch-keystore add-file` to load the credentials from the mounted files, then call the reload_secure_settings API to apply them without restarting.\n\nLet me first check which pods are running and understand the current cluster topology.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5666,"cache_read_input_tokens":29353,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5666},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"762c68f5-1845-4b98-81fa-231425769761","uuid":"da3f73ef-dc8e-4f90-995a-0127bb64098e","request_id":"req_011Ccf7qJqCKaYZTvBEcrqna"}
